No, it was clear not. The creature snarled only and tried to fly straight at Thassalin. Luckily, Thassalin, despite his size, was agile enough and dodged out of the way, but Nyssi let out a cry, as she nearly lost her footing on Thassalin's smooth scales.
"How can we kill it?", Nyssi screamed.
"Target their heads!"
"That will be difficult!"
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed but became slightly panicked as it was struck from behind by a fire beam. It hadn't noticed that it was no longer alone. It became even more panicked as Thassalin slowed down and then swung his tail against its head, veering it off course.
Growling and snarling, it flew upwards and spat into the air. Everything suddenly grew dark, as if the monster was sucking the light out of the sky and replacing it with a cloud of eternal night.
As he suddenly couldn't see anything anymore, Thassalin attempted a retreat. He felt as he scraped along the treetops before he finally fell into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot straight at him, dragging the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!", Tenuk screamed, as he slipped out of the cloud and began to circle, peering into the darkness below for Nyssi and Thassalin. "What are we to do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?"
Below the tree, Nyssi struggled to get to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her peculiar, supernatural healing powers were already taking effect. Unfortunately, that wasn't the case for Thassalin, who was exhausted and leaning against the only tree that hadn't collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made a great effort to reach Thassalin, but she could hardly see two meters in front of her. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in that shadow, something was screaming and shrieking.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi to the ground, knocking her down. However, she noticed that the tail was only wildly thrashing about and not attempting to strike her specifically. The beast, or the little that Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped at the shadows it had created with its claws. Something shot through the darkness, struck the monster, and disoriented it.
Suddenly a gunshot rang out through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and remained motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, heavily panting as he held his rifle.
"That was probably... The craziest shadow leap I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kabel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But as he spoke, the color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow hue.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers, but he rarely used them, as most people found them unsettling and quite intimidating. Nyssi hadn't known, however, that Kayel could also employ these powers in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving suggested that he was quite surprised as well.
"Are you alright?"
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something, I'll be okay in a moment." Kayel gazed at his handiwork while Tenuk descended, landed beside him, and resumed his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could see what it was. Its skin was a deep, glossy black and slick, but the slime stuck firmly to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could even ask what the hell they were facing, something shrieked and leapt out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to skid to a stop at Nyssi's feet. Nyssi wasn't taking any chances. She grabbed her shotgun, fired instinctively at its head, and the creature died on the spot.
"Oh no...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before awkwardly shutting off the engine and stepping out of the truck. "Uh, that wasn't exactly intentional. Are you all okay?"
"You missed the whole action," Tenuk scolded. "Where were you?"
"You just left me standing there. I came as fast as I could…", sighed Retvik. "May I ask, what are those dreadful creatures?"
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had managed to get back on his feet. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed but not too severely injured.
"You KILLED THE CORRUPTED ONES! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WENT AWAY WHEN CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean that terrifying God-monster being that we... helped to kill?"
"Yes, exactly that. Maybe there's more to it. But I couldn't shoot straight. I didn't have a firearm. And two against one is unfair, isn't it?" Thassalin hobbled over to Kayel and patted him on the head. "Thanks a lot, little one. You remind me of my old friend Arkadin. Just not so murderous and not so skilled at killing entire universes."
"Uh... thanks... I think...", shrugged Kayel. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitively dead beasts. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the ornamented Death God dagger, and began to saw off one of the beast's horns. Next, she started on the second one. But as soon as Nyssi was finished, the beasts suddenly burst into flames and transformed into a heap of ash in the blink of an eye. The same thing happened to the horns she had cut off.
"So, that's both practical and impractical at the same time...", sighed Nyssi. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
